  "title": "Upstream and Downstream Filtering",
  "concept": "A quality-control system can filter at entry or filter after entry by removing bad items later—when production cost drops to near-zero, the second strategy fails because pollution arrives faster than the system can clean, forcing a shift to stricter gates at submission.",
  "interactiveId": "4ec69c96-0b57-4ad5-8a2b-7feb67dc463b",
  "sourcePieceId": "94bf18c5-035c-4c32-9f23-2d19466a2c1a",
